From Table 1, “Status of the Account of the Treasurer of the United States,” total operating balance:
- FY 1953 = 4,187
- FY 1954 = 6,207

Treat these as zero-coupon prices one period apart under constant continuously compounded yield:
P_t = F e^{-yT}
P_{t+1} = F e^{-y(T-1)}

So
P_{t+1}/P_t = e^{y}

For a zero-coupon bond, Macaulay duration equals maturity T. Using the same constant yield, consistency of the two observed prices implies
P_t = P_{t+1} e^{-y}
and in general the duration parameter is the time-to-maturity measured in periods. With only two observations one period apart, the implied Macaulay-style duration that makes the pair consistent is exactly 1 period, since the price evolution over one observation interval for a zero is governed by one unit of time passage.

